key_concepts.explanation:
A class is a BLUEPRINT or TEMPLATE for creating objects. It defines what data (fields) and what actions (methods) objects of that type will have. The class itself is NOT an object -- it is the plan.

Real-world analogy: An architect's blueprint for a house. The blueprint defines: 3 bedrooms, 2 bathrooms, a kitchen (data). It also shows what you can do: open doors, turn on lights (actions). But the blueprint itself is not a house -- you BUILD houses FROM it.

Class syntax:
  class ClassName {
      // fields (data)
      // constructors (how to build)
      // methods (behaviour)
  }

Naming convention: Class names use PascalCase (first letter of each word capitalised): Dog, BankAccount, StudentRecord.

A class is a custom data type. Just like int holds numbers and String holds text, your class holds whatever combination of data you design.

Practice tip: Before writing a class, ask: What DATA does this thing have? What can it DO? The answers become your fields and methods.

