public class BankAccount {
    private String owner;
    private double balance;

    public BankAccount(String owner, double initial) {
        this.owner = owner;
        this.balance = Math.max(0, initial); // no negative balance
    }
    public double getBalance() { return balance; }
    public void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) balance += amount;
    }
    public boolean withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0 && amount <= balance) {
            balance -= amount;
            return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
}

key_concepts.explanation:
Getters and setters are the standard way to access private fields:

GETTER (accessor): Returns the field value. Convention: getFieldName() or isFieldName() for booleans.
  public String getName() { return name; }
  public boolean isActive() { return active; }

SETTER (mutator): Sets the field value with optional validation.
  public void setName(String name) { if(name != null) this.name = name; }
  public void setAge(int age) { if(age >= 0 && age <= 150) this.age = age; }

When to skip the setter: If a field should never change after construction (immutable), provide only a getter. Example: a person's date of birth.

Common beginner mistake: Writing getters/setters that just pass through without validation. If there is no validation, question whether you need the setter at all.

Naming convention: getX/setX for most types. isX for boolean getters. These conventions are used by tools and frameworks (JavaBeans standard).

